<TITLE> Distant Bay depression prompts signal 1 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 29 (bdnews24.com)  The depression in the southwest and adjoining southeastern Bay of Bengal moved to the northwest and was stationary in the mid-west and adjoining segments of the Bay Monday, a weather bulletin said. Meteorologist Sanaul Haque of the Metrological Department told bdnews24.com that the depression was stationary at a point 1,545km southwest of Chittagong port, 1,500km southwest of Cox's Bazar and 1370km southwest of Mongla port at about 6:00am Monday. The depression might strength further and move in a west, northwesterly direction. A met office special bulletin reported a wind-speed of 40km to 50km per hour in squalls and gusts at the depression centre whipping up the sea around it. The Met office asked the maritime ports of Chittagong, Cox's Bazaar and Mongla to hoist distant cautionary signal number 1 until further notice. All fishing boats and trawlers have also been asked to stay near the shoreline and proceed with caution. bdnews24.
